[2]
Date: Tue 23 May 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters News Alert, 23 May 2006 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L23546831.htm>

Romanian PM says bird flu not imported from EU
-----------------------------------------------
Romanian Prime Minister Calin Tariceanu on Tuesday [23 May 2006] dismissed
media allegations that imports of live poultry from Hungary and Slovakia
have caused a series of recent bird flu outbreaks across the country.
Local media, quoting a leaked report by the country's secret service SRI,
reported chicken farms in Transylvania brought sick birds from the 2
European Union-member states.
"I heard about this speculation that imported chicken brought the virus
into Romania. That's not true. I can tell you that there is no proof that
imports from Hungary and Slovakia triggered the new outbreaks in Romania,"
Tariceanu told private television station Realitatea TV. "I saw the SRI
report."
In the latest outbreaks, the virus spread from one chicken farm in the
county of Brasov, some 170 km (106 miles) north of Bucharest, after it sold
live chickens to peasants without health or veterinary certificates, the
agriculture minister said.
The SRI decided to make public its report on Tuesday [23 May 2006]
following repeated media requests. The report does not say that bird flu
definitely came from abroad but says: "The SRI cannot exclude the
hypothesis that the outbreak might have been caused by imports of birds."
It noted that chicken farms in Brasov have imported domestic birds from
Hungary, Slovakia and the Netherlands since January 2006 with health and
veterinary certificates.
Romania has reported more than 40 bird flu outbreaks over the past 2 weeks,
mostly in Brasov, just a month after the strain was said to have been
eradicated in the Black Sea state.
Tariceanu said the country's sanitary-veterinary authority and the farm
ministry had launched an investigation to determine the cause of recent
bird flu outbreaks.
Last Wednesday [17 May 2006], prosecutors issued warrants for the arrest of
2 owners of the Brasov farms. Another 7 people were being investigated for
allegedly spreading the virus.
The European Union candidate has culled nearly half a million birds since
discovering the 1st bird flu case in the Danube delta, Europe's largest
wetlands, last October 2005.
It has not reported any cases in humans.
